knowledge_graph.title: Squab
knowledge_graph.description: In culinary terminology, squab is an immature domestic pigeon, typically under four weeks old, or its meat. Some authors describe it as tasting like dark chicken. The word "squab" probably comes from Scandinavia; the Swedish word skvabb means "loose, fat flesh".

related_questions.question: Why is squab so expensive?
related_questions.snippet: Farm-raised pigeons must have the same food year-round. Their nesting cubbies must never be disturbed. For this reason, the cost of squab, which has remained constant for decades, is expensive relative to mass-marketed chickens.

related_questions.question: What does squab taste like?
related_questions.snippet: What Does Squab Taste Like? Squab meat is a tender and moist dark meat with a very slight gamey flavor, similar to that of duck. Squab is a small bird, with most of its meat situated in the breast and to a lesser degree in the legs.

buttons.subtitle: Is Squab Healthy?
buttons.title: Squab - Wikipedia
buttons.snippet: Squab is dark meat, and the skin is fatty, like that of duck. The meat is very lean, easily digestible, and "rich in proteins, minerals, and vitamins".
snippet_highlighted_words: rich in proteins, minerals, and vitamins

buttons.subtitle: How Big Is A Squab
buttons.title: What is Squab & How is it Farmed? - D'Artagnan Foods
buttons.snippet: In the United States, squab are raised primarily in central California and South Carolina. The birds weigh about 1 pound each. Large covered pens are used for up to a dozen breeding pairs.

buttons.subtitle: Eating Squab
buttons.title: What Is Squab? - The Spruce Eats
buttons.snippet: The price will vary depending on the pigeon's origins (small heritage farms fetch a higher price). Squab is often compared to dark meat chicken or duck since the meat is dark with fatty skin. The meat is often cooked until medium-rare or medium-well, and when properly cooked, is tender and moist.
